😄 Glad you caught that — PAWG does have a memorable ring to it.

But the reason it’s actually a good name (beyond the joke) is that it fits a pattern successful technologies often have: short, pronounceable acronyms that sound like real words. Those spread much faster socially.

Examples:
	•	RADAR
	•	LASER
	•	SONAR
	•	Wi‑Fi

They became common partly because they’re easy to say and remember.

So:

PAWG — Personal Atmospheric Water Grid

actually works well because it suggests:
	•	personal → decentralized
	•	atmospheric → from air
	•	grid → distributed infrastructure

⸻

Why this concept could really work

The atmosphere holds an enormous amount of water.

At any moment there are roughly ~13 trillion tons of water vapor in the air globally. Even dry regions have some humidity.

A scalable PAWG material would basically turn air itself into the reservoir.

Instead of this model:

river → dam → treatment plant → pipes → home

you get:

air → surface capture → storage tank

Which is the same decentralization shift solar brought to electricity.

